ve mistaken it for a sudden yelp of unmanly fear, but trust me. It was a battle cry.\n\n- Jim Butcher, My Big Fat Supernatural Wedding\n|\nTo realize your greatest strengths, you must first overcome your greatest weaknesses.\n\n- Matshona\n|\nWe can only find those faults in others that already exist within us, and the same goes for those things we admire about them.\n\n- Stephen\n|\nGreat endurance, great strength.\n\n- Lailah Gifty Akita, Think Great: Be Great!\n|\nIt's your destiny to be here, Dana.''Oh really. How nice. Is it Brandon's destiny to be here too?''Yep.\n\n- James L. Rubart, Soul's Gate\n|\nYou had a choice: you could either strain and look at things that appeared in front of you in the fog, painful as it might be, or you could relax and lose yourself\n\n- Ken Kesey, One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest\n|\nAnd Mother does not hate her; actually, she fears Damaya. Is there a difference? Maybe.\n\n- N.\n|\nWhat use is Order without Chaos to challenge its rule? And by the same standard, what lies ahead for us if nothing opposes our ways?\n\n- Louise Cooper, The Master\n|\nFaith is secured by adversity, but endangered by security.\n\n- Margaret\n|\nYou surround yourself with amazing, grade-A talent, and you're going to have to lift your game. You kind of thrive just by being around such people.\n\n- Joe\n|\nTruth brought to public light recruits the best of us to work for change. On the other hand, even the best-intentioned 'noble lie' ultimately discredits the finest of causes.\n\n- Christina Hoff Sommers, Who Stole Feminism?: How Women Have Betrayed Women\n|\nOne of the saddest things I hear as I travel is 'I don't know enough to be a feminist.' Or even 'I'm not smart enough to be a feminist.' It breaks my heart.\n\n- Gloria\n|\nI think that she is everything I have ever loved about our religion distilled down to fit into one person, everything about the faith that is both selfless and responsible.\n\n- Ann Patchett, This is the Story of a Happy Marriage\n